description.text:
Add radio control to a plastic 1/24 model with this printed pan. You will likely have to adjust the size and layout of the pan for your specific model, mine mounts a 1965 Pontiac Catalina 2+2. This is a fun way to get an RC model of an unusual car, Revell/Monagram make a ton of great models, most should fit on this pan with some tweaking. I have now converted 2 different models and made a number of minor changes to the design to improve both reliability and the assemble experience.
The code went through a major overhaul and is much more modular and easier to alter. If you want to make a pan for you own model start by making a copy of the "64_dodge_330.scad" (better body mounts) or "60s_Pontiac.scad" file. Everything you need to change should be in that file, the other files have all of the boilerplate that should be able to be reused. The gears are from GregFrost - thing # 3575

Notes: Tires and the spur gear for the motor print in ninja flex, the rest in PLA or what ever floats your boat. Ninja flex needs to be printed slowly, so be sure to use recommended settings for the tires. You will also want to decrease the floor thickness, or the back side of your tires will be much stiffer than the front. Print the gears at your highest quality and be sure to clean them up with a hobby knife to make sure they mesh properly. They will still be a bit loud, but the better the print the quieter they are. After you run it a bit to wear them in some 3 in 1 oil will help.

Assembly seems hard, but isn't too bad Add your own electronics: your radio of choice, a 230 electric motor, and 10A ESC, and a 6 gram servo. I mount the body to the chassis, the motor to the motor mount and servo to the chassis with hot glue. Some hot glue will also solid up your body and hold down random wires. You need 2 8x4x3 bearings (rear) and 2 6x3x3 (front) bearings. Retain the front bearings with an M3 nut on the spindle. A short length of 1/16 drill rod makes the axle for the reduction gear. A paperclip and a few 4-40 1/4 screws round out the list of other things you need. Note that the front suspension is created by the chassis flex, so don't let the body of your model rest on the pan forward of the inset. You may thicken the pan (or add a shim) if it sags too much. There is a PDF with more comprehensive instructions and photos attached. Put the spindles on the front axel then use the 4-40 screws to attach the front axel to the tabs on the pan. The steering cross arm can be secured to the offsets on the spindles with a short length of 1.75mm filament. Set the 6 gram servo on the front of the pan with its arm on the left side, pointed straight up in the centered position. The servos tabs should be in front of the stops. Bend your paper clip to create a link between the servo arm and the steering cross arm. Once you have this adjusted put a bead of hot glue around the servo to hold it in place. The front tires slip on the PLA hubs, and then on the spindles with the bearing flanges on the outside. Secure with an M3 nut on each side. Break them in so they turn smoothly. If they are too tight your car will be quite erratic. The rear axle passes though the motor mount on the larger bearings. Once your gears are meshing properly hot glue the motor down. Don't worry about the motor specifics, the 20 year old junk 230 I had laying in my drawer will light the tires like you wouldn't believe. Screw the motor mount to the chassis. There are a number of holes, but you only need 3 screws. The battery box will hold AA sized lithium's (note: those are 3.7 volt not 1.5 volt like normal AAs). Use some copper wire (or copper sheet) to make the battery contacts. The batteries, radio, and esc will have to go in the body of your model, YMMV but if you push hard enough it will all fit! :-)

And BOTH motors pushed as far towards the back as sensible,
without obstructing the screw heads. then ..
I recommend, loosely fitting the back left port on the dolly,
making sure that the teeth are facing away from you.
next through the slider, over the top pulley, towards you,
around left motor pulley.
all the way to the back left pulley, through the slider (yes at a strange angle) around the back right,
into the slider, and tie off on the front upper corner of the dolly. do not attempt to tighten the belt yet. fit the second belt, and gradually balance the tension, by moving the tie points inward,
and finally pulling motors toward front. note if there is a big difference in tension, then the slider will get pulled out of square. The belts do not need to be twangy, but firm. If you have them i relay do recommend the use of those spring clips.

title: Oil Filter Removal Tool, No Mess

description.text:
Description Fits 65.5mm 14 flute oil filters.
This is an oil filter removal tool designed to divert and funnel excess oil through the tool and out the bottom. This is helpful for oil filters that are mounted vertically (as mine is). When removing my filter, excess oil would run down the side of the filter and get all over my hand which made it really hard to hold and unscrew the filter (especially if the oil was still hot). This tool has channels in the side which route the excess oil though the inside of the tool and reduces the mess. Some other notable features of this tool:
  • The flow channels provide extra grip for removing the filter.
  • The funnel hole at the bottom fits a 1/2 ratchet wrench just in case the filter is really stuck on there. Note: the wrench needs to be removed after loosening the filter since the wrench will block the drain hole.
  • The tool acts as a general funnel as well. The end of the tool/funnel fits nicely inside the opening of a 1 quart or 1 gallon oil container. This keeps the tool/funnel stable while pouring the old oil back in the containers. Note: the size of the container opening somewhat differs between brands so it might not fit for all oil containers.
    • EDIT: 11/28/2015: After using the removal tool I made some slight changes to the design, the new part is named "oil_filter_drain_V02.STL". This includes changing the funnel slope angle from 40 to 45 degrees. I thickened and angled the bottom of the drain channels because a little oil seeped through at that location. I also changed the ratchet wrench size to a 1/2" so that the funnel drained quicker. I initially hesitated to go with the 1/2" size because it would result in less structure around the wrench opening, but I think it will still be strong enough. EDIT: 11/29/2016: I added a smaller version that should fit 63.5 mm (2.5 inch) filters. Some of the smaller MicroGuard or Wix filters are this size. It should be noted that I haven't tested this size out yet. I just realized this weekend that aftermarket oil filter I picked up was smaller than the OEM ones I was using previously, So it won't get test until the next oil change
